- Yeah, yeah, yeah.

11:01.108 --> 11:02.800
♪

11:02.834 --> 11:04.008
"Hey, a lot of foreigners.

11:04.042 --> 11:05.837
Lot of--lot of money."
[laughs]

11:05.872 --> 11:07.045
- [laughs]
I think we're paying them

11:07.080 --> 11:09.082
to not play music.
- [laughing]

11:09.116 --> 11:10.704
Yeah, right, right.

11:10.739 --> 11:13.327
♪

11:13.362 --> 11:15.226
- So you teach here.

11:15.260 --> 11:17.331
Uh, you were educated
in the States?

11:17.366 --> 11:20.093
- Yes, yeah.
I got my second full ride

11:20.127 --> 11:22.889
when I was teaching
as a Scholar-In-Residence

11:22.923 --> 11:24.511
at the University
of California.

11:24.545 --> 11:26.720
- And your subject was
the Nixon years.

11:26.755 --> 11:28.826
The--during that period.
- Yeah, yeah.

11:28.860 --> 11:30.517
After World War II.

11:30.551 --> 11:32.864
- You are also a--
a man of the cloth.

11:32.899 --> 11:34.176
A man of faith.
- [laughing]

11:34.210 --> 11:36.730
- Uh, so the right man
to talk to.

11:36.765 --> 11:39.043
We've been
largely advised that...

11:39.077 --> 11:40.734
[stammering]

11:40.769 --> 11:42.218
We will make people
uncomfortable

11:42.253 --> 11:44.393
if we even discuss
the year 1965.

11:44.427 --> 11:46.119
- [laughing]
The--the year

11:46.153 --> 11:48.052
of living dangerously.
- The year

11:48.086 --> 11:49.778
of living dangerously.
- Yeah.

11:49.812 --> 11:52.194
What happened was, basically
the Communists were accused

11:52.228 --> 11:54.817
of launching a coup
against the government,

11:54.852 --> 11:56.750
and because of that
there was kind of

11:56.785 --> 11:59.132
a justification
for killing people

11:59.166 --> 12:01.065
who were suspected
of being Communists.

12:01.099 --> 12:02.549
- And who were they?

12:02.583 --> 12:06.277
- They're just villagers
or people who...

12:06.311 --> 12:08.555
in a very bad way
associated with

12:08.589 --> 12:11.144
or connected with the
Indonesian Communist Party.

12:11.178 --> 12:12.490
- Right.

12:12.524 --> 12:15.769
[crowd chanting
in foreign language]

12:15.804 --> 12:18.047
- Indonesia boasts one
of the world's

12:18.082 --> 12:19.808
most bizarre leaders.

12:19.842 --> 12:22.431
Then, three weeks ago,
the Communists staged a coup.

12:22.465 --> 12:25.917
But it misfired,
and the army struck back.

12:25.952 --> 12:27.816
Michael Charlton reports.

12:27.850 --> 12:30.094
- Indonesia's revolution
is still fiercely on the boil

12:30.128 --> 12:32.959
as the systematic round-up
of Communists goes on.

12:32.993 --> 12:35.444
- With its leaders either
captured or killed,

12:35.478 --> 12:36.652
the Communist force collapsed.

12:36.686 --> 12:38.930
- The army led a hunt
for party officials,

12:38.965 --> 12:40.587
slaughtering the largest
Communist party

12:40.621 --> 12:42.969
outside the Iron Curtain.
- General Suharto

12:43.003 --> 12:45.109
has taken advantage
of the passion stirred

12:45.143 --> 12:47.594
to try and swing
public opinion hard against

12:47.628 --> 12:49.251
their rivals.

12:49.285 --> 12:52.426
The army now control
all news and information.

12:52.461 --> 12:55.429
[dramatic music]

12:55.464 --> 12:57.500
♪

12:58.985 --> 13:01.435
- The actual number
who were killed were between

13:01.470 --> 13:04.197
half-a-million to one million.

13:04.231 --> 13:06.302
And many more were imprisoned,

13:06.337 --> 13:09.305
tortured, and things like that.

13:09.340 --> 13:12.170
- Is it in the interests
of, uh--

13:12.205 --> 13:14.000
uh, Indonesians

13:14.034 --> 13:16.934
to be fully aware

13:16.968 --> 13:18.867
of what happened in '65?

13:18.901 --> 13:21.835
Has Indonesia as a country
reconciled itself

13:21.870 --> 13:23.319
to those events?

13:23.354 --> 13:26.150
- Is there eagerness to know?

13:26.184 --> 13:27.876
Yes, there is.

13:27.910 --> 13:29.981
There are people who--
many people.

13:30.016 --> 13:33.157
At the same time,
there was also fear.

13:33.191 --> 13:36.470
So many people,
they kept silent to...

13:36.505 --> 13:39.853
avoid their family members
being implicated.

13:39.888 --> 13:41.924
So yes, there is a lot
of eagerness,

13:41.959 --> 13:44.064
but at the same time
there a lot of fear.

13:44.099 --> 13:45.410
- Yeah.

13:45.445 --> 13:48.586
- And so the real
political situation is...

13:48.620 --> 13:52.003
- More complicated.
- Yeah, more complicated.

13:52.038 --> 13:55.006
[hypnotic sitar music]

13:55.041 --> 14:01.426
♪

14:01.461 --> 14:03.428
[car honks]

14:03.463 --> 14:09.883
♪

14:09.918 --> 14:13.024
- What about everyday life
thrills you here?

14:13.059 --> 14:14.957
You wake up in the morning
and walk outside...

14:14.992 --> 14:18.064
- Well, you cannot meet
nicer people, Tony.

14:18.098 --> 14:20.273
I mean everyone treats
everyone else

14:20.307 --> 14:22.240
with respect and kindness.

14:22.275 --> 14:25.071
It's engrained
in the culture here.

14:25.105 --> 14:27.107
- [speaking native language]
- You just still see

14:27.142 --> 14:29.385
certain things here that are
just gone in other countries.

14:29.420 --> 14:31.042
You know, you still
have got people

14:31.077 --> 14:32.975
grilling sauté on the street...

14:34.252 --> 14:36.047
You've got people
wheeling around

14:36.082 --> 14:39.602
sort of wooden carts
that have gone elsewhere.

14:39.637 --> 14:41.915
At the same time,
you've got 16 million people

14:41.950 --> 14:44.711
who have smart phones
all on social media,

14:44.745 --> 14:46.057
and, you know,
that's opening up

14:46.092 --> 14:47.956
massive opportunities.

14:47.990 --> 14:51.062
To be a journalist here now
is just, uh, privilege.

14:51.097 --> 14:54.065
[indistinct chatter]

14:54.100 --> 14:56.102
[mellow music]

14:56.136 --> 14:59.105
[indistinct chatter]

14:59.139 --> 15:03.626
♪

15:03.661 --> 15:05.490
- Yeah, is this--
so is this the, uh,

15:05.525 --> 15:07.976
unofficial, uh,
foreign correspondents club?

15:08.010 --> 15:09.425
- It is.
- Very much so.

15:09.460 --> 15:10.737
- Yes indeed, yeah.
- How long you been

15:10.771 --> 15:13.222
living here?
- Most of 18 years.

15:13.257 --> 15:16.018
- How long you been living...
- Uh, I've had two stints.

15:16.053 --> 15:17.192
I'm about six years.

15:17.226 --> 15:19.056
Yeah, so I count back.
- Same, I've done two stints.

15:19.090 --> 15:21.058
- So how are things going?

15:21.092 --> 15:23.577
I mean, this--this is
a Democracy now, yes?

15:23.612 --> 15:25.303
- Oh, it is.
- I've always called it

15:25.338 --> 15:27.616
a microcosm of--of all
the good and bad

15:27.650 --> 15:31.137
in the world, 'cause Indonesia
has everything.

15:31.171 --> 15:33.622
Democracy, it has pollution;

15:33.656 --> 15:36.245
it has environmental
degradation;

15:36.280 --> 15:37.626
it's got human rights abuses.

15:37.660 --> 15:39.283
There's a lot
of problems here,

15:39.317 --> 15:41.009
but one of the great things
going on is these elections

15:41.043 --> 15:43.252
are free and fair,
and everybody knows it.

15:43.287 --> 15:45.289
- A popular president,

15:45.323 --> 15:47.463
relative peace in the land.

15:47.498 --> 15:49.983
Free speech?
- Oh, absolutely.

15:50.018 --> 15:52.986
- But there--there are
two subjects that

15:53.021 --> 15:56.196
there is a real reluctance
to talk about or reconcile,

15:56.231 --> 15:58.302
and it's kind of weird.

15:58.336 --> 15:59.993
The years 1965

16:00.028 --> 16:02.030
and 1975--

16:02.064 --> 16:04.342
there isn't much appetite
to look at that.

16:04.377 --> 16:06.482
Why?
- For reputational reasons...

16:06.517 --> 16:08.139
- Yeah.
- Uh, as much as anything,

16:08.174 --> 16:10.003
but also potentially
legal reasons as well,

16:10.038 --> 16:12.799
so the--the two main
perpetrators of the--

16:12.833 --> 16:15.284
of the massacre
were the military

16:15.319 --> 16:17.459
and the mass Islamic groups.

16:17.493 --> 16:18.667
[crowd shouting]

16:18.701 --> 16:21.739
Um, the groups who are
moderate these days

16:21.773 --> 16:24.673
but at that time
and with that hysteria

16:24.707 --> 16:27.158
they were involved in this

16:27.193 --> 16:29.505
kind of brutal pogrom.

16:29.540 --> 16:30.817
This was sort of
hand-to-hand,

16:30.851 --> 16:33.199
slitting throats,
garroting people,

16:33.233 --> 16:35.166
burying them in mass graves--

16:35.201 --> 16:37.513
very nasty, nasty stuff.

16:37.548 --> 16:39.136
And then the second reason is,

16:39.170 --> 16:42.725
there was an intensive campaign
of propaganda.

16:42.760 --> 16:45.073
which portrayed this, uh,

16:45.107 --> 16:47.075
massacre as a--
as a honorable attempt

16:47.109 --> 16:50.388
by Suhato to put down
a Communist coup.

16:50.423 --> 16:53.219
- Is it even useful
for Indonesians

16:53.253 --> 16:56.187
to look at that
extraordinarily...

16:56.222 --> 16:58.051
painful...

16:58.086 --> 17:00.433
awful period of time?
- We journalists write--

17:00.467 --> 17:02.366
you know, you gotta believe

17:02.400 --> 17:05.748
allowing these stories
to be told is--

17:05.783 --> 17:08.717
you know, is gonna be
to the good.

17:08.751 --> 17:10.201
- You know, I don't know.

17:10.236 --> 17:12.100
I want to believe that,
I really do.

17:12.134 --> 17:15.103
I do believe that,
but certainly

17:15.137 --> 17:17.070
the West doesn't much want
to talk about it.

17:17.105 --> 17:18.520
- No.
- [laughing]

17:18.554 --> 17:20.211
- We were...
- Culpable.

17:20.246 --> 17:21.557
[laughs]
- But yes, we were--

17:21.592 --> 17:23.559
we were in deep.

17:23.594 --> 17:25.458
But what is it--
Henry Kissinger walks

17:25.492 --> 17:27.253
into a bar--
it sounds like a joke.

17:27.287 --> 17:28.806
- [laughs]

17:28.840 --> 17:31.464
- Henry Kissinger and a penguin
walk into a bar.

17:31.498 --> 17:33.604
Uh, I'm not asking
what you'd do,

17:33.638 --> 17:35.088
but what would--

17:35.123 --> 17:37.608
would it displease you
if I walked over

17:37.642 --> 17:39.403
and punched Henry Kissinger
in the face?

17:39.437 --> 17:40.611
- [laughs]
- Would you find that

17:40.645 --> 17:42.233
entertaining?
- I--I would.

17:42.268 --> 17:44.408
- Would you have a frisson
of pleasure, even?

17:44.442 --> 17:45.754
Would you feel injustice is--

17:45.788 --> 17:47.100
is in some small way served?
- [laughs]

17:47.135 --> 17:50.483
You hate Henry.
- I--I hate him, yeah.

17:50.517 --> 17:52.761
Because in my travels,
I stumble across

17:52.795 --> 17:54.314
his good works
everywhere I go.

17:54.349 --> 17:55.798
- Right.

17:55.833 --> 17:56.903
Let's do this.
[laughs]

17:56.937 --> 17:58.905
- I'll rabbit-punch.
[all laughing]

17:58.939 --> 18:01.494
- No, kidney punch.
- Cheers.

18:01.528 --> 18:03.323
- Cheers, guys.

18:03.358 --> 18:05.325
[indistinct chatter]

18:05.360 --> 18:08.604
[plane engines roaring]

18:09.916 --> 18:12.677
- Java is Indonesia's
seat of power,

18:12.712 --> 18:15.163
but this home to millions
is just one

18:15.197 --> 18:19.270
of seemingly countless islands
across the archipelago.

18:19.305 --> 18:20.789
[adventurous music]

18:20.823 --> 18:23.619
Bali endures as an island
of legends.

18:23.654 --> 18:26.622
Of magic and spirits.

18:26.657 --> 18:28.624
Where ancient
Animist traditions

18:28.659 --> 18:31.593
bled with Hindu
and Buddhist beliefs.

18:31.627 --> 18:33.871
♪

18:33.905 --> 18:36.287
Ceremonies and offerings
are an attempt

18:36.322 --> 18:39.187
to bring harmony between
the upper world of the gods

18:39.221 --> 18:41.499
and the lower world
of the demons...

18:41.534 --> 18:42.673
[instrument rings]

18:42.707 --> 18:45.158
With man balanced in between.

18:45.193 --> 18:47.816
[crowd shouting]

18:47.850 --> 18:50.267
♪

18:50.301 --> 18:53.201
- [speaking native language]

18:53.235 --> 18:55.203
[exclaims]

18:55.237 --> 18:58.309
♪

18:58.344 --> 19:00.725
- Who is the hero?

19:00.760 --> 19:03.245
Who is the villain?
[crowd shouting]

19:03.280 --> 19:06.490
Who decides what is
right or wrong?

19:06.524 --> 19:08.181
♪

19:08.216 --> 19:10.666
Bali is as much an island
of the gods

19:10.701 --> 19:13.290
as it is the demons.

19:13.324 --> 19:16.362
[engines roaring]

19:18.605 --> 19:21.574
[tropical music]

19:21.608 --> 19:28.891
♪

19:30.652 --> 19:32.654
[whistle blowing]

19:32.688 --> 19:34.725
[indistinct chatter]

19:34.759 --> 19:37.245
[whistle blowing]

19:37.279 --> 19:40.213
♪

19:40.248 --> 19:43.009
[rousing pop music]

19:43.043 --> 19:45.356
♪

19:45.391 --> 19:48.359
[man vocalizing]

19:48.394 --> 19:52.398
♪

19:52.432 --> 19:54.676
- ♪ Feel the music

19:54.710 --> 19:55.884
♪

19:55.918 --> 19:58.266
♪ Can you feel the mu--

19:58.300 --> 20:03.547
♪

20:03.581 --> 20:05.583
- [imitating heavy beat]

20:05.618 --> 20:07.896
[slurps]

20:08.759 --> 20:10.726
I hate Daft Punk.

20:10.761 --> 20:12.590
[men cheering]

20:12.625 --> 20:19.908
♪

20:21.323 --> 20:22.738
Do you have a shot
of the, uh, people

20:22.773 --> 20:25.741
getting, uh, massages
by the pool while eating?

20:25.776 --> 20:27.743
♪

20:27.778 --> 20:30.229
This is an Emmy-winning shot,
dude.

20:32.300 --> 20:34.440
It's happening
right over there.

20:34.474 --> 20:39.479
♪

20:39.514 --> 20:41.999
- ♪ Yo

20:42.033 --> 20:44.795
- So this, too, is Bali,
I guess.

20:44.829 --> 20:47.073
Or it is now.

20:47.107 --> 20:49.386
Thank you, Jimmy Buffet,
for taking a big dump

20:49.420 --> 20:51.008
on the world.

20:51.042 --> 20:53.286
[smacks lips, sighs]
Another wagyu slider,

20:53.321 --> 20:54.425
my good man.
- [indistinct]

20:54.460 --> 20:56.841
- Yes, thank you.

20:58.326 --> 21:01.639
By weight, how much human waste

21:01.674 --> 21:04.504
is generated by your average...

21:04.539 --> 21:07.576
person on vacation?

21:07.611 --> 21:09.095
Look around you.

21:09.129 --> 21:11.408
Do the math.

21:11.442 --> 21:13.755
[lighthearted music]

21:13.789 --> 21:15.929
I want a water sample.

21:15.964 --> 21:17.448
♪

21:17.483 --> 21:18.829
I'm telling you,

21:18.863 --> 21:21.659
the fecal coliform count

21:21.694 --> 21:23.765
has got to be interesting.

21:23.799 --> 21:26.319
[overlapping chatter]

21:26.354 --> 21:28.666
I'm sure there's
a metaphor here.

21:28.701 --> 21:30.668
[slurping]

21:30.703 --> 21:32.429
[men chattering, cheering]

21:32.463 --> 21:34.810
[all laughing]

21:34.845 --> 21:37.503
- Oh!
[all laughing]

21:37.537 --> 21:38.814
- Am I bitter?

21:38.849 --> 21:40.402
Am I just old?

21:40.437 --> 21:43.405
Do I just have, like,
a predisposition,

21:43.440 --> 21:46.650
an instinctive hatred
of young people?

21:46.684 --> 21:48.859
Perhaps.

21:48.893 --> 21:51.482
[smacks lips]
Enjoy the moment.

21:51.517 --> 21:53.484
The words of Baba Ram Dass,

21:53.519 --> 21:54.899
"Be here now."

21:54.934 --> 21:56.487
But I am here now.

21:56.522 --> 21:58.524
[man laughing]

21:58.558 --> 22:00.698
♪

22:00.733 --> 22:03.356
I--I'm not actually
having sliders.

22:03.391 --> 22:04.737
♪

22:04.771 --> 22:07.153
I mean, you eat those
[...] things.

22:07.187 --> 22:10.467
♪

22:12.020 --> 22:14.988
[upbeat rock music]

22:15.023 --> 22:18.406
[distant engine revving]

22:20.408 --> 22:23.376
[gentle percussion]

22:23.411 --> 22:28.381
♪

22:28.416 --> 22:31.591
[man speaking indistinctly]

22:31.626 --> 22:38.702
♪

22:41.946 --> 22:44.915
- People who've seen
"Eat Pray Love"...

22:44.949 --> 22:47.573
who were inspired
to come to Bali...

22:47.607 --> 22:49.057
♪

22:49.091 --> 22:51.197
And do yoga...

22:51.231 --> 22:52.578
♪

22:52.612 --> 22:55.581
They have a romantic notion.

22:55.615 --> 22:58.929
♪

22:58.963 --> 23:01.207
They want to improve

23:01.241 --> 23:03.416
their lives in a...

23:03.451 --> 23:04.624
♪

23:04.659 --> 23:07.731
Physical and spiritual way.

23:07.765 --> 23:08.904
♪

23:08.939 --> 23:13.081
They would like to have
and experience...

23:13.115 --> 23:15.808
that they can remember.

23:15.842 --> 23:17.603
[indistinct chatter]

23:17.637 --> 23:19.777
You mention Bali
and people think "paradise."

23:19.812 --> 23:22.159
both: Of course.

23:24.955 --> 23:27.923
[ambient music]

23:27.958 --> 23:30.926
[rousing music]

23:30.961 --> 23:38.209
♪

23:58.713 --> 24:00.266
- Oh, wow.
- Thank you.

24:00.300 --> 24:01.267
Oh, here they come.

24:01.301 --> 24:03.511
The babi guling.
- Oh, yeah.

24:03.545 --> 24:04.546
I remember this dish.

24:04.581 --> 24:06.652
I love it, of course.

24:06.686 --> 24:09.275
- Maybe we can just talk
really quickly about the food?

24:09.309 --> 24:11.277
No, I--I'll get it in a VO,

24:11.311 --> 24:13.210
'cause I've had it before.

24:13.244 --> 24:14.556
We don't need to talk
about this food

24:14.591 --> 24:15.799
'cause I know it
very, very well.

24:15.833 --> 24:17.628
I will speak incredibly
knowledgably of it

24:17.663 --> 24:19.181
in voice-over.
Trust me.

24:19.216 --> 24:20.597
- You've been here before,
right?

24:20.631 --> 24:22.564
- I have been here
I think 11 years ago,

24:22.599 --> 24:24.704
and it was a very
different-looking place

24:24.739 --> 24:27.500
even then, 11 years ago.
- 11 years is too long.

24:27.535 --> 24:30.227
- Yes.
- [laughs]

24:30.261 --> 24:32.022
- How did you get into
the yoga business?

24:32.056 --> 24:34.887
Did you anticipate it was--
it would become so big,

24:34.921 --> 24:37.130
or did it start small?
- Not really, honestly.

24:37.165 --> 24:39.857
It was when the "Eat Pray
and Love" was shooting

24:39.892 --> 24:41.687
in the island.

24:41.721 --> 24:43.999
[man speaking indistinctly]

24:44.034 --> 24:45.691
[serene music]

24:45.725 --> 24:48.521
- So tell me how many
customers you do in a day.

24:48.556 --> 24:50.730
- 300 to 400 people.

24:50.765 --> 24:52.836
- That's a big increase.
- It's--it's really huge.

24:52.870 --> 24:55.528
'Cause you see the traffic,
how crazy it is.

24:55.563 --> 24:57.599
- It is crazy.
- [laughing]

24:57.634 --> 24:58.807
Dealing with the traffic.

24:58.842 --> 25:01.085
- I mean, it's worse
than Manhattan.

25:01.120 --> 25:03.812
[cars honking]

25:03.847 --> 25:06.021
- Uh, right now that--
we have two big problem

25:06.056 --> 25:07.022
right now.

25:07.057 --> 25:08.714
First is waste,

25:08.748 --> 25:10.854
second is traffic.

25:10.888 --> 25:12.890
♪

25:12.925 --> 25:14.202
Is the tourism bad?

25:14.236 --> 25:15.272
Yes, it have its bad side.

25:15.306 --> 25:17.274
Is the tourism good?
Yes, of course.

25:17.308 --> 25:19.276
Right?

25:19.310 --> 25:20.726
What is Bali?

25:20.760 --> 25:22.244
What is Bali and its people?

25:22.279 --> 25:23.556
What is Bali and its culture?

25:23.591 --> 25:25.834
What part of this
could be supported

25:25.869 --> 25:27.698
by the people who come
to Bali?

25:27.733 --> 25:30.287
What kind of people
do we want to come to Bali?

25:30.321 --> 25:33.290
[inquisitive marimba music]

25:33.324 --> 25:35.568
♪

25:35.603 --> 25:36.776
- I think you've kind of
put your finger

25:36.811 --> 25:39.883
on something that a lot
of people have not.

25:39.917 --> 25:42.230
Because you don't want
to just do yoga--

25:42.264 --> 25:45.578
you wanna do yoga
in reasonable distance

25:45.613 --> 25:47.131
of this.

25:47.166 --> 25:48.616
♪

25:48.650 --> 25:50.618
Of these temples.

25:50.652 --> 25:52.378
♪

25:52.412 --> 25:53.966
If you come to Bali
and it looks

25:54.000 --> 25:56.244
exactly like Cancún

25:56.278 --> 25:58.626
and Miami, why the [...]

25:58.660 --> 26:01.042
get on a plane
all the way to Bali?

26:01.076 --> 26:03.734
♪

26:03.769 --> 26:06.737
[adventurous music]

26:06.772 --> 26:13.779
♪

26:28.794 --> 26:31.244
- This one the three
most piratical places

26:31.279 --> 26:33.108
on the planet.

26:33.143 --> 26:34.903
It's pretty safe around here,
now.

26:34.938 --> 26:36.422
It wasn't to be
in the early days

26:36.456 --> 26:39.425
when we were filming here.

26:39.459 --> 26:42.635
You first arrived
in Indonesia in '65, right?

26:42.670 --> 26:44.672
- That's right,
but it was pretty--

26:44.706 --> 26:45.776
pretty hairy, then.

26:45.811 --> 26:48.365
- Given that you arrived
at absolutely

26:48.399 --> 26:50.816
the worst possible time...
- Yep.

26:50.850 --> 26:54.026
- What was it about the place
that, uh, compelled you

26:54.060 --> 26:55.855
to come back?
- Uh, unexplored regions,

26:55.890 --> 26:58.927
tropical animals,
ancient civilizations,

26:58.962 --> 27:01.965
long memory amongst the people,
mysticism.

27:01.999 --> 27:05.831
Everything a school-boy
would obviously love.

27:05.865 --> 27:08.005
[wind blowing]

27:08.040 --> 27:10.663
[pulley squeaking]

27:15.185 --> 27:16.704
- Your, uh, training--

27:16.738 --> 27:19.396
correct me if I'm wrong--
psycho-anthropology?

27:19.430 --> 27:22.848
- Yes.
- Now, are there...

27:22.882 --> 27:24.884
through-lines, or is there

27:24.919 --> 27:28.163
any connectivity
between belief systems?

27:28.198 --> 27:30.821
- They're different,
but they're all united

27:30.856 --> 27:32.720
by a common theme--
that they believe

27:32.754 --> 27:34.722
in the reality
of the invisible world.

27:34.756 --> 27:36.862
They believe it's stronger
than what we think

27:36.896 --> 27:38.208
is the reality.

27:38.242 --> 27:40.037
You know, what we can touch
and measure and weigh.

27:40.072 --> 27:42.868
They would all share the belief
that this is illusion.

27:42.902 --> 27:44.214
That this is only the surface

27:44.248 --> 27:46.837
of another, greater reality
beneath it.

27:46.872 --> 27:49.737
In that,
they're fairly constant.

27:49.771 --> 27:52.740
[mystical music]

27:52.774 --> 27:54.431
♪

27:54.465 --> 27:57.434
This is Nusa Penida.

27:57.468 --> 28:00.368
This was a penal colony
for Bali.

28:00.402 --> 28:02.266
They put their criminals here.
- Right.

28:02.301 --> 28:05.407
- And they also believe
that it is the home

28:05.442 --> 28:07.202
of the Leyaks--
the witches,

28:07.237 --> 28:09.446
the black magicians.

28:09.480 --> 28:11.862
♪

28:11.897 --> 28:14.382
- [speaking native language]

28:14.416 --> 28:17.799
♪

28:17.834 --> 28:20.526
- This island has not
been invaded, uh, like Bali.

28:20.560 --> 28:22.804
- No, it hasn't.

28:22.839 --> 28:24.185
♪

28:24.219 --> 28:26.877
- Hey, there's a bachelor party
going on there.

28:26.912 --> 28:28.810
- [laughing]

28:28.845 --> 28:30.743
- Oh, no.

28:30.778 --> 28:32.296
Just messing with you, man.

28:32.331 --> 28:34.229
Wow, beautiful.

28:36.197 --> 28:38.958
[upbeat rock music]

28:38.993 --> 28:42.237
[waves crashing]

28:43.480 --> 28:46.448
[mellow music]

28:46.483 --> 28:53.524
♪

29:06.814 --> 29:09.782
[food sizzling]

29:09.817 --> 29:16.824
♪

29:17.376 --> 29:19.412
- Wow.
- That's, uh--

29:19.447 --> 29:21.449
that's some big lobsters.
- These have to be

29:21.483 --> 29:24.452
the biggest local lobsters
I've ever seen.

29:24.486 --> 29:25.591
♪

29:25.625 --> 29:27.938
- Wow.

29:27.973 --> 29:31.252
♪

29:31.286 --> 29:34.082
In the West, we tend
to think of things

29:34.117 --> 29:35.808
in a binary way.

29:35.843 --> 29:37.948
There's good and evil,

29:37.983 --> 29:40.364
life, death.

29:40.399 --> 29:43.367
You've seen every variety
of human behavior...

29:43.402 --> 29:45.473
uh, in this part of the world.

29:45.507 --> 29:48.890
Always a notion
of light and dark,

29:48.925 --> 29:50.892
good and evil...

29:50.927 --> 29:53.101
just not absolute ones?

29:53.136 --> 29:55.103
- Uh, you know, we call Bali

29:55.138 --> 29:56.553
"the island of the gods."

29:56.587 --> 29:58.486
That's a sort of slogan
for the tourism industry,

29:58.520 --> 30:00.384
but it's equally
an island of the demons,

30:00.419 --> 30:02.179
I mean, I--I've always
found useful, in anthropology,

30:02.214 --> 30:05.010
this concept of the left
and right cranial hemispheres.

30:05.044 --> 30:06.874
- Right.
- The left is the thing

30:06.908 --> 30:09.221
that we are over-dominant in
in the West,

30:09.255 --> 30:12.465
handles the rational,
practical, consecutive thought.

30:12.500 --> 30:14.329
Here, it's
the opposite imbalance.

30:14.364 --> 30:15.572
It's the other way round.

30:15.606 --> 30:18.506
The right is the intuitive,
holistic,

30:18.540 --> 30:20.542
access to everything
we've ever been,

30:20.577 --> 30:21.958
access to our genetic...
- That's our right brain.

30:21.992 --> 30:23.476
- Memory.
Exactly.

30:23.511 --> 30:24.961
- So they know stuff
we don't know?

30:24.995 --> 30:27.032
- They definitely know stuff
we don't know.

30:27.066 --> 30:30.035
[gentle percussive music]

30:30.069 --> 30:34.039
♪

30:34.073 --> 30:36.938
- Given all the time
you've spent in Indonesia,

30:36.973 --> 30:38.940
do you experience life
differently,

30:38.975 --> 30:40.079
or in any way similarly

30:40.114 --> 30:42.979
to the people here
look at it?

30:43.013 --> 30:46.499
- No, I don't think I do see it
the way people here see it.

30:46.534 --> 30:48.881
I like to think that I can see
what it is

30:48.916 --> 30:50.538
that they're seeing,
as it were

30:50.572 --> 30:52.885
but I've got
a broader perspective.

30:52.920 --> 30:54.059
Course, I'm a Westerner,

30:54.093 --> 30:56.095
and a foreigner
in a strange land.

30:56.130 --> 30:58.339
I'll never be considered
an Indonesian.

30:58.373 --> 31:02.274
I--I'm enriched
by being here,

31:02.308 --> 31:05.380
because there's
a greater variety

31:05.415 --> 31:09.212
of human experience
going on here.

31:09.246 --> 31:11.697
- Yeah, tell me about
the funerals,

31:11.731 --> 31:13.975
'cause I--
we were attending one.

31:14.010 --> 31:15.597
- Y-y-you are?
You will be?

31:15.632 --> 31:17.082
- Yes.

31:17.116 --> 31:17.772
- Well, a Balinese funeral

31:17.806 --> 31:19.049
is a very sobering phenomenon,

31:19.084 --> 31:20.223
especially for us Westerners,

31:20.257 --> 31:22.052
who distance ourselves
from death.

31:22.087 --> 31:23.191
- Mm-hmm.

31:23.226 --> 31:24.606
- They spend quite
a long time

31:24.641 --> 31:26.091
doing these
beautiful offerings,

31:26.125 --> 31:27.989
all of it
to up in flames.

31:28.024 --> 31:29.128
- Ah.

31:29.163 --> 31:30.923
- So it's ephemeral art,

31:30.958 --> 31:33.374
and the idea is that
we, too, are ephemeral,

31:33.408 --> 31:37.033
and, uh, this is why it's
quite an extraordinary thing

31:37.067 --> 31:38.966
that you actually
light the match

31:39.000 --> 31:41.934
that consumes
your loved one,

31:41.969 --> 31:43.625
but it's in your face...

31:43.660 --> 31:47.008
- Mm-hmm.
- That we are not our bodies,

31:47.043 --> 31:49.597
because they really believe
in an afterlife.

31:49.631 --> 31:52.496
They really believe
that you will be coming back,

31:52.531 --> 31:55.465
and you will be joining
your ancestors in the meantime.

31:55.499 --> 31:57.260
It may be wrong,
but it's wonderful

31:57.294 --> 31:58.951
to be able to believe that,

31:58.986 --> 32:01.160
and to derive all the warmth

32:01.195 --> 32:03.024
and strength and benefit of it.

32:03.059 --> 32:05.164
Is this all human poetry,

32:05.199 --> 32:07.511
or is there something in it?

32:07.546 --> 32:09.306
- Yeah, I wonder.
I mean, I thought about,

32:09.341 --> 32:11.170
you know, as one does...

32:11.205 --> 32:13.000
- [laughs] Yeah.
- You know, how I want to go.

32:13.034 --> 32:14.104
How do you want to go?

32:14.139 --> 32:15.347
- I'd be burned.

32:15.381 --> 32:17.142
I can handle cremation.
- You want a party?

32:17.176 --> 32:19.178
I mean...
- Oh, I'd rather a party, yes.

32:19.213 --> 32:21.146
- You would?
- How about you?

32:21.180 --> 32:23.182
You want them all to cry,
don't you?

32:23.217 --> 32:24.356
[laughs]
- No, no.

32:24.390 --> 32:26.013
Leave me in the jungle.

32:26.047 --> 32:28.084
- Okay.
- I don't want a party.

32:28.118 --> 32:30.120
Um...
- Okay.

32:30.155 --> 32:31.673
- "Reported dead."

32:31.708 --> 32:33.123
- Okay.

32:33.158 --> 32:34.366
- You know,
what actually happens

32:34.400 --> 32:36.713
to my physical remains

32:36.747 --> 32:39.474
is of zero interest to me...
- Doesn't matter.

32:39.509 --> 32:42.167
- Unless it can provide
entertainment value.

32:42.201 --> 32:43.720
Throw me
into a wood chipper

32:43.754 --> 32:46.033
and spray me into Harrods,
you know,

32:46.067 --> 32:48.483
at, uh, middle
of the rush hour.

32:48.518 --> 32:50.554
- [laughs]
- That would be pretty epic.

32:50.589 --> 32:53.212
I wouldn't mind
being remembered in that way.

32:57.492 --> 32:59.770
[upbeat rock music]

33:00.599 --> 33:03.153
[energetic percussive music]

33:03.188 --> 33:10.229
- [speaking native language]

33:13.267 --> 33:14.199
- Wayang

33:14.233 --> 33:16.580
is not necessarily

33:16.615 --> 33:19.031
entertainment
for the people.

33:19.066 --> 33:20.688
Most of the time,
it's performed

33:20.722 --> 33:22.207
for the unseen.

33:22.241 --> 33:25.037
♪

33:25.072 --> 33:28.075
[bell ringing]

33:29.110 --> 33:30.698
That's why
it's a shadow play.

33:30.732 --> 33:32.734
It's also
for the shadow world.

33:32.769 --> 33:36.221
♪

33:36.255 --> 33:37.567
Balinese have
a lot of magical thinking.

33:37.601 --> 33:40.673
Often, we believe that

33:40.708 --> 33:44.574
what happens in the real world
is a consequence

33:44.608 --> 33:46.334
of what is happening
in the shadow world.

33:46.369 --> 33:48.750
That's why
there's so much offerings

33:48.785 --> 33:51.098
and appeasements.

33:51.132 --> 33:54.446
Every day,
we make offerings:

33:54.480 --> 33:56.586
love notes,
thank-you notes,

33:56.620 --> 33:57.828
left around to the spirits,
saying,

33:57.863 --> 34:01.108
"Thank you for keeping
everything in balance."

34:09.461 --> 34:12.291
[rooster crows]

34:13.430 --> 34:16.571
So today is the final rites
of the human.

34:16.606 --> 34:19.471
Once the ashes
are scattered to the sea,

34:19.505 --> 34:21.887
then begin the rites
of the spirit.

34:21.921 --> 34:24.821
- So who will attend
the funeral today?

34:24.855 --> 34:26.443
- The family, of course,

34:26.478 --> 34:28.135
but cremations in Bali

34:28.169 --> 34:29.791
are very much
a communal affair,

34:29.826 --> 34:32.104
so the village runs it.

34:32.139 --> 34:34.727
It's not just the family.
- Right.

34:34.762 --> 34:37.730
[all chanting, bell ringing]

34:37.765 --> 34:38.800
♪

34:38.835 --> 34:40.181
People's attitudes

34:40.216 --> 34:42.459
towards the passing of a life,

34:42.494 --> 34:44.634
towards death,

34:44.668 --> 34:46.291
funerals, wakes,

34:46.325 --> 34:47.809
different here
than in the West.

34:47.844 --> 34:51.192
- Very much so.
- No weeping

34:51.227 --> 34:52.780
and rending of garments.
- There's--there is

34:52.814 --> 34:54.299
a lot of...
- There is?

34:54.333 --> 34:56.128
- It's--

34:56.163 --> 34:58.682
at the bathing ceremony
of the body,

34:58.717 --> 35:01.513
that is when
the mournful event

35:01.547 --> 35:03.135
becomes a joyous occasion.

35:03.170 --> 35:05.344
- Right,
but the funeral itself...

35:05.379 --> 35:06.863
- Is a joyous occasion,

35:06.897 --> 35:08.692
especially the cremation.
It's a big send-off.

35:08.727 --> 35:10.280
It's a big party
to send a spirit

35:10.315 --> 35:11.454
to the afterlife.

35:11.488 --> 35:13.180
- We are not talking
about the end.

35:13.214 --> 35:14.422
- No.

35:14.457 --> 35:15.630
Life is cyclical.

35:15.665 --> 35:17.218
It's very much a circle.

35:17.253 --> 35:18.702
- So this is something
to be happy about.

35:18.737 --> 35:23.328
- Yes, definitely.

35:23.362 --> 35:26.331
[lively percussion]

35:26.365 --> 35:33.579
♪

35:34.615 --> 35:37.376
[cheering]

35:37.411 --> 35:44.694
♪

35:47.869 --> 35:50.182
The priest
is throwing out rice,

35:50.217 --> 35:52.184
along with money.
- Oh, we're--

35:52.219 --> 35:54.635
- And essentially,
this action

35:54.669 --> 35:56.982
is to confuse
and misdirect

35:57.016 --> 35:59.364
the spirits that might try to--

35:59.398 --> 36:01.573
try to follow the...

36:01.607 --> 36:04.403
[cheering, shouting]

36:04.438 --> 36:11.721
♪

36:16.415 --> 36:18.279
- Love the sound.
It's beautiful.

36:18.314 --> 36:19.867
- So--
- The gamelan.

36:19.901 --> 36:21.903
- It reverberates
throughout your body,

36:21.938 --> 36:24.423
and the idea
is that that noise

36:24.458 --> 36:26.218
shatters the illusion

36:26.253 --> 36:28.772
between the seen
and the unseen worlds.

36:28.807 --> 36:36.263
♪

36:38.748 --> 36:41.716
[shouting]

36:41.751 --> 36:48.965
♪

37:01.909 --> 37:04.877
[chanting]

37:04.912 --> 37:12.333
♪

37:14.853 --> 37:18.305
[droning sound]

37:50.958 --> 37:53.305
[upbeat metallophone music]

37:53.340 --> 37:55.997
- The state of mind
is very important

37:56.032 --> 37:58.310
for your next journey.

37:58.345 --> 38:00.312
♪

38:00.347 --> 38:03.004
This is where you frame
that big send-off

38:03.039 --> 38:04.489
to the next life,

38:04.523 --> 38:06.318
and of course,

38:06.353 --> 38:08.458
that journey is the--
the mystery,

38:08.493 --> 38:09.977
the unknown,
because eventually,

38:10.011 --> 38:11.668
the soul
will be reincarnated

38:11.703 --> 38:13.498
back here.

38:13.532 --> 38:20.815
♪

38:23.093 --> 38:25.579
[upbeat rock music]

38:26.096 --> 38:29.065
[metallophone music]

38:29.099 --> 38:36.072
♪

38:36.106 --> 38:40.076
- [speaking native language]

38:40.110 --> 38:42.803
♪

38:42.837 --> 38:45.737
- The shadow play story
of Bhima Swarga

38:45.771 --> 38:49.085
is often told as part
of funerary rites

38:49.119 --> 38:50.500
for many reasons.

38:50.535 --> 38:53.538
Heaven and hell
are allegories,

38:53.572 --> 38:55.919
not truths.

38:55.954 --> 38:57.507
Heaven and hell exist

38:57.542 --> 39:00.441
right here,
on the mortal plane.

39:00.476 --> 39:02.926
♪

39:02.961 --> 39:05.446
No tears should be shed

39:05.481 --> 39:07.483
during the cremation ceremony.

39:07.517 --> 39:11.452
Tears only hold back
the soul of the departed.

39:11.487 --> 39:14.835
At sundown,
ashes will be released,

39:14.869 --> 39:18.459
returned to the purity
of the sea.

39:18.494 --> 39:22.118
Time is circular,
as is life.

39:22.152 --> 39:24.396
Death is but the beginning

39:24.431 --> 39:26.847
of another journey.

39:26.881 --> 39:29.850
[woman singing]

39:29.884 --> 39:34.475
♪

39:38.962 --> 39:41.931
[light rock music]

39:41.965 --> 39:49.007
♪

40:14.653 --> 40:17.622
[bell music]

40:17.656 --> 40:24.698
♪

40:47.755 --> 40:50.517
[speaking native language]

40:50.551 --> 40:53.520
[gentle music]

40:53.554 --> 41:00.803
♪

41:23.964 --> 41:28.658
- All stories
should end on a beach.

41:28.693 --> 41:31.558
All the good ones do, anyway.

41:31.592 --> 41:35.320
Why should this one
be any different?

41:35.354 --> 41:42.569
♪
